        <p><i>
                <big>The Taj Mahal is not just a monument of marble and stone; it is a timeless poem etched in white, a
                    whisper of eternal love spoken through centuries. Standing gracefully on the banks of the Yamuna
                    River, it seems to float between earth and sky, catching the first blush of dawn and the quiet glow
                    of moonlight with equal splendour.
                    <br><br>
                    Commissioned by Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal, the Taj is more than
                    a tomb — it is the embodiment of devotion, the physical manifestation of a heart's undying promise.
                    Its delicate minarets, intricate carvings, and perfect symmetry sing the language of love in a way
                    that words often fail to capture.
                    <br><br>
                    As the sun moves across the sky, the Taj Mahal transforms, changing hues from soft pink at dawn to
                    dazzling white in the afternoon, to a gentle golden under the evening moon. It reminds every soul
                    that visits it that love, in its truest form, transcends time, space, and even death.
                    <br><br>
                    The Taj Mahal is not merely India’s crown jewel; it is humanity’s gentle reminder that beauty born
                    of love can endure forever.</big></i></p>

